 The technology works by flowing cells along a tiny microfluidic chip [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/b3931f73-a97b-45b0-b48a-69a614780d6b?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] where they are co=
mpressed as they flow through a narrow channel. When they re-expand, the mo=
lecular payload used to reprogram them flows into the newly available intra=
cellular space. According to the founder, the vision is for cell-based ther=
apy to evolve into a two-day process that is =E2=80=9Cmanufactured and admi=
nistered similar to what is done with dialysis today.=E2=80=9D
Taken together, these investments paint a picture of several distinct manuf=
acturing strategies vying for supremacy in a rapidly growing market. One po=
ssible future closely resembles the present: Big Pharma invests in a growin=
g number of centralized factories that produce cell-based therapies much li=
ke we do now=E2=80=94round-trip flights included. Alternatively, Cellares a=
nd its competitors envision a future where we dramatically shrink the footp=
rint of the existing factories using robotics and software, making it possi=
ble to distribute them much closer to hospitals around the world. The third=
 and most extreme solution is to invent processes that circumvent the need =
for factories altogether. Imagine CAR-T therapy evolving into a routine out=
patient procedure administered as soon as a cancer is detected.
Ultimately, the final balance between these different candidate solutions w=
ill be determined through market competition. As Marc Andreessen argues [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/350c66d5-bf00-43bc-8093-913ca86c681d?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CThe t=
echno-capital machine makes natural selection work for us in the realm of i=
deas.=E2=80=9D The selection function here is simple: which technology and =
business model can deliver the cheapest, fastest, and safest cell-based the=
rapies to patients in need?
CAR-T began its life as a controversial academic idea. Now, it=E2=80=99s an=
 approved product with potentially curative effects for each blood cancer p=
atient that is dosed. The major open questions are ones of scaling and engi=
neering=E2=80=94the scientific question of efficacy has been answered in th=
e clinic. This is a real breakthrough moment for the field of cell-based th=
erapy.
The thing is, CAR-T only scratches the surface of the full vision for cellu=
lar medicine. Let=E2=80=99s turn our attention to the biomedical frontier, =
where a whole host of engineered cell therapies are poised to make the same=
 leap that CAR-T did: from concept to practice.
The broader arsenal of cell-based therapies
In 2013=E2=80=94only a year after the pair of papers describing the initial=
 clinical CAR-T results=E2=80=94three faculty members from the University o=
f California, San Francisco (UCSF) published an article [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/7d5d0398-dd86-449b-a31b-5c3ed2e0c357?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] laying out a vision for cell-ba=
sed therapeutics as a =E2=80=9Cthird pillar=E2=80=9D of modern medicine alo=
ngside small molecules and the first wave of biologically derived big molec=
ules. In their estimation, CAR-T was the first of four proposed =E2=80=9Cki=
ller apps=E2=80=9D for cellular medicine.
The four applications were:
Engineered immune cells. CAR-T is one example of the broader vision to engi=
neer immune cells to recognize and cure disease.
Induced pluripotent stem cell (iPSC) therapy. The 2012 Nobel Prize was awar=
ded to two scientists who discovered that mature human cells can be transfo=
rmed back into stem cells=E2=80=94the type of cell that can differentiate i=
nto any other cell type. This has enormous implications for medicine.
Living bacterial cell therapies. Human cells don=E2=80=99t need to be the o=
nly target for therapeutic engineering. Our bodies contain more bacterial c=
ells than human cells. The microorganisms that live on and in us represent =
another unique opportunity for genetic reprogramming.
Multicellular logic systems. Why stop at engineering one cell type? What if=
 we could develop therapies that leveraged cell-to-cell communication to ac=
hieve a precise therapeutic effect?
These predictions have fared well so far. As we=E2=80=99ve seen, CAR-T ther=
apy has demonstrated that directly engineering immune cells is a viable the=
rapeutic strategy. Still, CAR-T represents only one possible cell type, and=
 one possible receptor. In a recent essay on immune engineering [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/ac961768-4cb9-4ea5-ad27-d996e1c9e21b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I argued that this rep=
resents only a tiny sliver of the possible design space. For starters, ther=
e are a lot of other immune cells to engineer.
Already, we=E2=80=99re seeing the engineered CAR receptor start to be porte=
d to other immune cell types. Natural Killer (NK) cells=E2=80=94a well-name=
d cell that specializes in targeted cell killing similar to T-cells=E2=80=
=94have also been equipped with CARs [ https://substack.com/redirect/9240be=
e1-5028-4298-bcaa-5bf7eec37f5d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. The same is true for macrophages [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/eb8edefe-f96c-4d52-8c64-08fe7a570245?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], another type of immune cell=
 that is capable of gobbling up entire cells like a molecular Pac-Man. This=
 generalization of the technology across the immune system highlights a way=
 that cell-based medicine differs dramatically from the world of small and =
big molecules: reusability and composition is possible. One small molecule =
binds to one cellular target, period. A synthetic receptor resembles a piec=
e of biological software=E2=80=94it is a genetically encoded module that ca=
rries out the same function in any cell that it is integrated into.
What other biological software can we write? One clear direction is to desi=
gn better CARs with more bells and whistles=E2=80=94another distinct benefi=
t of working in genetic design space where iteration is much more tractable=
 than in chemical space. The names of these new programs illustrate the evo=
lution at work. For example, T-cell Redirected for Universal Cytokine-media=
ted Killing receptors=E2=80=94or TRUCKs=E2=80=94encode a molecule called IL=
-12 that serves to signal to other cells that they should activate into can=
cer killers. From CARs, to more heavy duty TRUCKs, engineered immune recept=
ors will continue to be refined over time by genetic engineers.
Another massive benefit that cells provide is the ability to program logic =
operations. Rather than sensing and binding to a single antigen, the design=
 space extends to the world of genetic circuits that integrate multiple sig=
nals before triggering a response. SynNotch receptors rely on the activatio=
n of a cellular AND operation=E2=80=94A AND B need to both be present to ru=
n the CAR-T genetic program. This type of cellular computation will likely =
play a central role in the extension of immune engineering from blood cance=
rs to solid tumors.
As the frontrunner for successful cellular medicine, immunotherapy also ser=
ves as a test bed for how we actually deliver the biological software that =
we write into a patient's cells. The current paradigm of extracting T-cells=
 from the blood, engineering them, and then reintroducing them is called ex=
 vivo cell therapy=E2=80=94which is Latin for outside the body. As we=E2=80=
=99ve seen, this approach introduces a serious scaling limit on clinical ad=
option of cell-based therapies with our current manufacturing infrastructur=
e. What if we could engineer immune cells that we could store in biobanks l=
ike other biologics, and then use them when we need them?
This type of =E2=80=9Coff-the-shelf=E2=80=9D approach is referred to as all=
ogeneic cell therapy, because it requires infusing a patient with cells tha=
t aren=E2=80=99t their own. Much like organ transplants, the major roadbloc=
k for allogeneic cells is the threat of graft-vs-host disease, where the bo=
dy=E2=80=99s immune system recognizes the cells that are introduced to the =
blood as foreign and responds with a frontal assault=E2=80=94which can be l=
ife threatening. Several labs and companies are actively exploring ways to =
engineer donor cells to evade the immune system.
Achieving this is a hard genetic engineering problem. It would require knoc=
king out two sets of immune receptors, while simultaneously inserting the C=
AR sequence. A key breakthrough that makes this type of multi-edit design p=
otentially feasible is CRISPR=E2=80=94a gene-editing technology that receiv=
ed the 2020 Nobel Prize for making it possible to programmably edit the gen=
ome. One thing that makes all of this especially mindblowing is that the se=
minal CRISPR paper [ https://substack.com/redirect/9995057b-5c9b-46ac-a39f-=
3888f245f1dd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ] was published in 2012, right on the heels of the first CAR-T papers.
In one calendar year, we saw field-changing advances for cell-based therapy=
 (the CAR-T papers in 2011), gene-editing (the publication of CRISPR gene-e=
diting in 2012), and AI (the AlexNet moment [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/bdfd0059-78db-449c-9ebb-f643a34d8aa7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for deep learning in 2012). 8VC partner Fra=
ncisco Gimenez refers to it as the =E2=80=9CAnnus mirabilis [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/34d10465-5d3e-4a59-bb89-696a082670ac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for medicine [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/34d10465-5d3e-4a59-bb89-696a082670ac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=9D much like how muc=
h Einstein transformed physics with his four publications on the photoelect=
ric effect, Brownian motion, relativity, and mass-energy equivalence all in=
 1905.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a beautiful example of Intertwining Threads [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/f5f35bef-a82f-4bb4-9f9=
a-5676386c4937?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], as Packy would put it: =E2=80=
=9COne of the things that makes the future so hard to predict is that new t=
echnologies don=E2=80=99t operate in silos; they=E2=80=99re intertwining th=
reads that weave together in unpredictable ways.=E2=80=9D We=E2=80=99re see=
ing this property on full display in the life sciences: some of the first C=
RISPR companies such as Caribou Biosciences [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/e6dda984-4dc9-4e95-925c-e91c8836bf94?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and CRISPR Therapeutics [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/f7b23642-1ecf-4fcb-b34e-9edc81aefbda?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] are pushing the hardest to make=
 allogeneic cell therapies a reality. Next-generation T-cell engineering co=
mpanies like Arsenal Bio [ https://substack.com/redirect/1cfe4c97-0494-4594=
-b98a-a23b8a51a14d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ] are building extensive machine learning infrastructure to acce=
lerate the construction of new synthetic cell modules. It=E2=80=99s a story=
 of compounding exponentials=E2=80=94these inventions and discoveries don=
=E2=80=99t exist in isolation, they bleed into each other and are remixed i=
n new ways to accelerate progress.
CRISPR and AI aren=E2=80=99t the only technologies that are intersecting wi=
th cell therapy. We=E2=80=99ve already successfully scaled mRNA therapies (=
the recipient of this year=E2=80=99s Nobel Prize [ https://substack.com/red=
irect/6fff36a3-aab2-464c-b7c1-144add9af3ce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7Gn=
A_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]) to ship billions of COVID vaccine dos=
es around the world. Given the manufacturing challenges with ex vivo cell t=
herapy and the considerable scientific risk [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/4388b05d-d5cf-4a99-8fa6-25bf188675fc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] still surrounding the allogeneic alternativ=
es, what if we just used mRNA to program immune cells in vivo? There=E2=80=
=99s mounting scientific evidence that this might actually work. In a dream=
 team collaboration for the ages, several top researchers from Penn includi=
ng Carl June and Drew Weissman (the co-recipient of the mRNA Nobel) injecte=
d mice with a dose of mRNA containing the instructions to produce a CAR-T r=
eceptor [ https://substack.com/redirect/398ee4dc-78b1-4b4b-9d36-4f81b40e190=
3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. The=
 CAR was designed to bind to the FAP molecule on the surface of fibroblasts=
 in order to destroy scarring of the heart called cardiac fibrosis. The dos=
ed mice presented with reduced scarring. Already, a wave of  [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/92fc5f7f-ed6d-4145-8f19-717e2e94311a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]in vivo [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/92fc5f7f-ed6d-4145-8f19-717e2e94311a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] cell therapy companies [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/92fc5f7f-ed6d-4145-8f19-717e2e94311a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] are gearing up to en=
ter the clinic.
Between efforts in next-generation manufacturing and designs, off-the-shelf=
 cells, and in vivo genetic reprogramming, immune engineering is going thro=
ugh a renaissance. All of these new directions represent a single decade of=
 progress. Another decade from now, the state-of-the-art could look complet=
ely different.=C2=A0
Still, immune cells are only a single facet of the broader cell-based thera=
py revolution.
In modern biotech, analogies to computer science aren=E2=80=99t metaphorica=
l. The induced pluripotent stem cell (iPSC) revolution makes this crystal c=
lear. iPSC technology takes advantage of the beautiful nature of human deve=
lopment. We all begin life as a single cell and undergo genetically program=
med rounds of cell division. Most cells differentiate into a final cell typ=
e, like skin, lung, heart, and brain cells. Some cells don=E2=80=99t. These=
 cells=E2=80=94called stem cells=E2=80=94occupy certain niches in the body,=
 and can be stimulated to differentiate into multiple cell types, like a ve=
rsatile back-up player. In 2006, a research paper from the lab of a Japanes=
e stem cell scientist named Shinya Yamanaka demonstrated a result that bord=
ered on absurd: using a tiny cocktail consisting of only four genes, it=E2=
=80=99s possible to reprogram differentiated cells into =E2=80=9Cpluripoten=
t=E2=80=9D stem cells that can be differentiated into other cell types.
Think about that. Your skin cell, transformed into a neuron. Or muscle cell=
s. Or heart cells. This simple set of genes called =E2=80=9Creprogramming f=
actors=E2=80=9D (also referred to as Yamanaka factors) laid the basis for t=
he field of iPSC engineering. Now, scientists around the world are working =
to perfect the right cellular programs to convert iPSCs into every other ce=
ll type in the body. This has two immediate ramifications for medicine:
iPSCs as a model system to study disease.
iPSCs as a basis for autologous cell therapy=E2=80=94much like CAR-T therap=
y.
Instead of testing new drugs in mice, why not test them in actual patient-d=
erived cells? Some companies like Rarebase [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
4c645fee-7a17-4d9a-b71a-ebf450c89892?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] are already partnering with rare disease fou=
ndations [ https://substack.com/redirect/3765b84b-00db-4cc4-a1ce-355d960e09=
f7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to =
rapidly screen libraries of drugs in patient-derived iPSC models. Other com=
panies like bit.bio [ https://substack.com/redirect/36af5d37-1995-4c51-af15=
-4c4751ee4662?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] are working to ship iPSC disease models for every cell type to rese=
archers and companies as a product. They are also partnering with therapeut=
ics companies to produce iPSC-derived cell therapies=E2=80=94including immu=
ne cells [ https://substack.com/redirect/120c962f-f2b5-434c-adfc-c2b10f2c73=
c3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Much like for CAR-T therapy, researchers are asking the question: what if w=
e could skip the cell isolation step and reprogram cells in vivo? This appr=
oach, called partial reprogramming [ https://substack.com/redirect/4364736e=
-060b-414a-ac32-0516da517209?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], has emerged as one of the hottest potential longevi=
ty therapies. New longevity companies flush with cash like Retro Bioscience=
s (backed by $180M from Sam Altman [ https://substack.com/redirect/34858e06=
-e2f9-4216-a351-bd4521014b76?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]), NewLimit (backed by $40M of VC funding and $110M c=
ommitments from the founders Brian Armstrong and Blake Byers [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/8b3236bb-1889-4f9e-81d8-5cad99ed4c36?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]), and the goliath Altos La=
bs (launched with $3B in funding [ https://substack.com/redirect/cec0fce4-f=
4b5-42ae-954d-5f31905fbe9f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=94the largest private biotech funding to-date=E2=
=80=94and a collection of biotech luminaries including Yamanaka) are all ra=
cing towards cell reprogramming therapies.
Ultimately, this won=E2=80=99t only be for cells, but will be the basis for=
 entire organ systems=E2=80=94the full vision of regenerative medicine. Alr=
eady, researchers in Israel have produced stem cell derived embryo models a=
ll the way up to 14 days of development [ https://substack.com/redirect/dd5=
07b0c-32d2-4ed0-b30c-1c83bec6f1c7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. While this has immediate implications for the =
future of human reproduction=E2=80=94and companies like Conception [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/8d38c044-791b-443a-bba3-003ce489c4a2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] are pursuing this ap=
plication=E2=80=94it also opens the door to differentiating the embryos int=
o other tissues (and potentially organs) with identical genetics to a patie=
nt in need of a transplant.
Alright=E2=80=A6 engineered immune cells to kill cancer, and iPSC/reprogram=
ming therapies to cure, well=E2=80=A6 disease.
What about engineering the microbial cells and communities that inhabit the=
 human body?
When you first learn that your own cells are outnumbered by your microbial =
inhabitants, it can be a bit disconcerting. In the most recent estimates [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/d518556e-fd6e-4c2c-8576-0fc11f335ca1?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the human bod=
y consists of roughly 30 trillion cells=E2=80=94which is a lot, for sure=E2=
=80=94but not as many as the 38 trillion bacteria that live inside us. This=
 vast ecosystem of cells is collectively referred to as the human microbiom=
e. Much like the stages of grief, it=E2=80=99s possible to move from a plac=
e of fear=E2=80=94or even disgust=E2=80=94about this reality towards a plac=
e of awe, and even a reconceptualization of what it means to be a human. We=
 all contain multitudes [ https://substack.com/redirect/cb3e9258-06ec-4c57-=
8f86-e1a043510f5b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ]. More pragmatically, it opens up an entirely new strategy for i=
nterfacing with diseased human cells.
So far, the field of microbiome therapeutics has had a mixed track record [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/f98b796d-dcdc-4197-93b9-013627f85284?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. First met wi=
th extreme hype and a lot of funding, many of the first companies have expe=
rienced clinical setbacks. Trials have been placed on hold for safety conce=
rns. Companies have died. Some of the early science has been called into qu=
estion [ https://substack.com/redirect/4c1dd437-bc33-40e5-8122-924fa96bad12=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Ques=
tions have been raised about the ability to produce consistent and reliable=
 medicines, given that the first microbiome therapies have been sourced fro=
m human poop=E2=80=94a procedure called a fecal microbiota transplant. Seri=
ously.
Despite the shitty start, there are signs that microbiome therapies are sta=
rting to reach a higher technology readiness level [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/d8be314d-3b1e-40f2-ab68-41e7dd41d96e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. To start, the FDA approved the firs=
t oral microbiome therapy [ https://substack.com/redirect/d211e506-3f8d-47f=
d-9898-101387c0c488?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ] in April earlier this year. Produced by the Cambridge-based S=
eres Therapeutics [ https://substack.com/redirect/dce17430-5174-49f7-a728-1=
e1badade419?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ], the therapy (called Vowst) contains purified spores from a strain of=
 bacteria capable of outcompeting another strain called C. difficile that c=
an cause a serious gut infection. The fact that Vowst is going to be co-com=
mercialized by Nestl=C3=A9 indicates that it is ready to be scaled. Name an=
other company that ships top-notch espresso capsules, chocolates, and oral =
microbiome therapies. I=E2=80=99ll wait.
Closer to the frontier, things are getting even more sophisticated. It=E2=
=80=99s long been a goal to move beyond working with individual strains of =
bacteria. In the =E2=80=9Cthird pillar=E2=80=9D paper, the authors wrote: =
=E2=80=9CIn the future, the microbial community to be transplanted is likel=
y to be an artificial, well-characterized mixture of strains.=E2=80=9D Why?=
 You don=E2=80=99t want uncharacterized poop, but using only a single bacte=
ria is rate-limiting for complexity. A decade later, this is becoming a rea=
lity. In a massive effort from several top microbiome labs at Stanford, res=
earchers created a stable synthetic community of transplantable microbes co=
ntaining over 100 different organisms [ https://substack.com/redirect/73c41=
dcc-df72-491a-ba1b-1c71907239c2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Michael Fischbach, one of the =E2=80=9Cthird pil=
lar=E2=80=9D authors, was a senior author on this new study. Talk about cal=
ling your shots. This type of synthetic microbiome will enable much deeper =
mechanistic science and more rationally engineered microbiome therapies.
A stable synthetic microbiome opens the door to some of the more futuristic=
 ideas like engineered bugs that sense and respond to their environment, an=
d even produce small molecules or biologics directly in the body. Given the=
 mega-blockbuster sales of the first GLP-1 drugs (like semaglutide) for dia=
betes and obesity, this gets even more interesting. While semaglutide has b=
een forecasted to potentially produce $300B in annual sales [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/42255372-99f9-4750-b9bf-458e1718d1ae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the first generation of me=
dicines has been shown to introduce the risk of severe stomach complication=
s [ https://substack.com/redirect/3a83f494-3ccb-409e-bfcd-8be1e78d775b?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. For some =
of these medicines, up to 70% of patients experience serious side effects [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/5a4b891c-4d8b-40b6-b84c-7ccc7ef020cb?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. A logic-gate=
d microbial therapy that reduces stomach complications by tuning GLP-1 prod=
uction in response to the gut environment could become a blockbuster cell t=
herapy like nothing we=E2=80=99ve ever seen before.
This isn=E2=80=99t the only way that microbial and human cells could be use=
d in combination. As if Dr. William Coley=E2=80=99s research wasn=E2=80=99t=
 already vindicated enough, engineered microbes are now being used to boost=
 CAR-T therapy. The mechanism is absurdly cool. Bioengineers from Columbia =
University engineered a strain of nonpathogenic E. coli to infiltrate tumor=
s and deliver molecular =E2=80=9Ctags=E2=80=9D that mark the cancer for det=
ection and destruction by CAR-T cells.
Clearly, we=E2=80=99ve come a long way from Coley=E2=80=99s first toxin inj=
ections. We=E2=80=99re now using the toolbox of modern biotech to engineer =
sophisticated cells=E2=80=94and combinations of cells=E2=80=94for a potenti=
al curative effect across a wide range of diseases. These drugs are =E2=80=
=9Cpart drug and part device,=E2=80=9D and are like nothing we=E2=80=99ve e=
ver seen before in medicine.
So, what=E2=80=99s my point?
Even with all of this progress, I think we=E2=80=99re still in the earliest=
 innings for cell-based therapy. Let=E2=80=99s think back to the analogy of=
 medicine=E2=80=99s three pillars:
Small molecules
Big molecules
Cells
CAR-T does represent an entirely new type of medicine. But the GLP-1 exampl=
e illustrates that there could be real benefits to having cells produce big=
 molecules based on smart detection of signals inside the body. Couldn=E2=
=80=99t this also logically extend to small molecules? After all, some of o=
ur best small molecules are things that we discovered being produced by cel=
ls in the first place [ https://substack.com/redirect/cb587cdd-6d22-4689-95=
8d-aa94af2a50ff?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ]. So, in time, everything could become a subset of cell therapy:
Cells
Act as a medicine (like CAR-T)
Produce big molecules in response to the environment (like GLP-1)
Produce small molecules in response to the environment
Like we now look back in horror that people used to smoke on planes, our fu=
ture ancestors could be shocked that this wasn=E2=80=99t always the status =
quo in medicine. =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re telling me that for contraception,=
 women used to take oral doses of sex hormones that have widespread effects=
 throughout the body and brain [ https://substack.com/redirect/f2ed0afa-f1b=
8-403e-a219-481be171e86d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] instead of engineering commensal vaginal bacteria to sec=
rete computationally designed proteins that directly obstruct egg cells??? =
Sure grandma, let=E2=80=99s get you to bed.=E2=80=9D The list goes on. =E2=
=80=9CYou used to treat your diabetes with an insulin pump and an elaborate=
 dosing schedule instead of islet cell therapy [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/978665bb-e67d-45b1-bc2a-a3ac84e43c9e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]? Okay grandpa=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D
This is why, in the limit, cells are likely to be Medicine=E2=80=99s Endgam=
e.
At this point, we=E2=80=99re solidly in the realm of speculation. Many curr=
ent medicines already work so well that fancy programmable cell-based deliv=
ery wouldn=E2=80=99t be justified. Achieving a future with ubiquitous cellu=
lar medicines is an ambitious and long-term project. It=E2=80=99s why my ne=
wsletter is called The Century of Biology [ https://substack.com/redirect/a=
3947ea8-2f22-47c7-be84-50c0b49ebee2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], not The Decade of Biology. Still, as we gain=
 mastery of cell biology and engineering, large swathes of medicine are up =
for grabs. We=E2=80=99re on the cusp of a transition towards truly preventa=
tive, curative, and even regenerative approaches to treating disease.
If biotech continues to head this direction, it opens up important economic=
 questions. For decades, Irv Weissman, one of the pioneers of stem cell bio=
logy, has passionately argued that curative one-time cell therapies run cou=
nter to the interests of Big Pharma companies [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/382b2450-3b9c-4f41-bb90-9651f58f98eb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which introduces a serious barrier to tr=
ansforming medicine. They just want to keep selling you pills! In part, Wei=
ssman formed this viewpoint after one of the therapies he developed was can=
celed during the merger between Sandoz and CIBA to form Novartis [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/c83e2f3f-6d4b-4db5-8be3-bdc65baca2d3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=94the same compa=
ny would ultimately license CAR-T therapy from Penn for further development=
 and approval.
I think that we now have sufficient evidence that Big Pharma companies are =
very interested in developing cell therapies. Over time, we may actually ru=
n into the opposite problem: cell therapies may produce too much value for =
Big Pharma.
Right now, innovation in drug discovery is maintained by a tenuous balance =
between society, insurance companies, and drug developers that Peter Kolchi=
nsky of RA Capital refers to as the Biotech Social Contract. We collectivel=
y invest in basic research, which is then commercialized, patented and mark=
eted by private companies. But small molecule drugs are information product=
s=E2=80=94all of the value comes from the precious intellectual property (I=
P), not the actual chemicals, which are commodities worth very little. As a=
 result, when drug patents expire, prices rapidly plummet and society gets =
access to the medicine cheaply for the rest of time. It=E2=80=99s a pretty =
good deal. As Kolchinksy would put it, high branded drug prices are =E2=80=
=9Clike paying a mortgage, not rent.=E2=80=9D After the upfront investment,=
 we all own this generic drug armamentarium forever.=C2=A0
But how do you produce the generic version of a complex cell therapy? Even =
after the patents expire, the only companies able to produce these medicine=
s will be the ones that invested in the manufacturing and process infrastru=
cture to produce the branded versions of the therapy. How will new entrants=
 compete against the Scale Economies of large cell manufacturing facilities=
? Who will emerge to compete with Novartis to drive down the price of Kymri=
ah from $475,000 a dose?
This is why new approaches to manufacturing and cell therapy delivery are u=
tterly essential.
Cell-based cures for cancer, diabetes, and even aging are the potential rew=
ard for our continued investment in modern biotechnology. They represent a =
real opportunity to meaningfully reduce human suffering. To make these trea=
tments universally available, we=E2=80=99ll also need to scale our entire i=
nfrastructure layer for biomanufacturing. The scaling of nucleic acid vacci=
nes during the COVID pandemic showed us that this is possible. Now, we need=
 to do the same for cells.
We just went on a whirlwind tour of the past, present, and future of cell-b=
ased medicine. Hopefully it=E2=80=99s clear that the potential here is enor=
mous. Our growing arsenal of engineered immune cells, stem cells, and micro=
bial cells could redefine our relationship with disease.
Each therapeutic invention introduces complex new problems to solve, but if=
 we can realize the full potential of cell-based therapy, medicine will nev=
er look the same.
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/61338c6c-5b99-4379-aca8-d761b=
9b0d7d3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing and to Elliot [ https://substack.com/redirect/286ed2fb-dca6-4=
398-85d8-730b5e61cce0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for sharing his genius.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox with the =
Weekly Dose on Friday.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

