: 70%;"><em><span>Dr. Carl June, the relentless champion of CAR-T. Source: =
</span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/3768ecbf-78b3-4f37-9b27-8c4=
f46ff5717?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U" rel style=3D"text-decoration: underline;">Sanford Health Lorraine Cross =
Award</a></em></figcaption></figure></div><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>June&#821=
7;s motivation to improve cancer therapy came from a place of personal loss=
=2E He began his research career with a=
 focus on procedures to boost immune f=
unction in patients with HIV. It was only when his 41-year old wife was bat=
tling ovarian cancer that he dropped everything to pursue cancer immunother=
apy. The pivot was too late to impact his wife&#8217;s care, but her loss l=
it a fire that propelled him forward. There </span><em>needed</em><span> to=
 be a better approach to treatment.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64=
, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Motivated b=
y the preliminary designs and data around CAR-T, June launched the CART-19 =
study that Emily ultimately enrolled in. The name stems from the fact that =
the engineered receptors are designed to target CD19, a molecule only found=
 on the surface of B-cells&#8212;which are the type of blood cells that are=
 mutated in ALL. The result is a one-sided war between T-cells and B-cells =
where no B-cells are left standing. Over time, the body produces new B-cell=
s that are cancer-free.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The first patient doses&#8212;=
including Emily&#8217;s&#8212;got off to a rocky start. Just as had been pr=
edicted, hyper-stimulating the immune system with a foreign receptor was a =
risky business. After Emily&#8217;s third dose of CAR-T, she developed an i=
ntense fever, could barely breathe, and went into shock. For a moment in ti=
me, her life&#8212;and the future of this new procedure&#8212;hung in the b=
alance.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Emily&#8217;s lab orders were accelerated. Wit=
h new data in hand, her doctors learned that her interleukin-6 (IL6) levels=
 were off the charts. IL6 is a small signaling molecule that immune cells p=
ump out to trigger cascades of inflammation. For a second time, illness in =
June&#8217;s family shaped the course of cancer immunotherapy. His daughter=
 had recently been prescribed a medication targeting IL6 called Tocilizumab=
 to manage her case of juvenile rheumatoid arthritis. June had a long-shot =
idea: what if they dosed Emily with Tocilizumab to curb the inflammation?</=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In the eleventh hour, Emily&#8217;s prognosis rev=
ersed. Her shock quickly receded and her symptoms stabilized. Eight days la=
ter, a biopsy confirmed that the CAR-T procedure had been a success. To thi=
s day, her cancer is in complete remission. For Dr. Stephen Grupp, one of t=
he essential physicians overseeing Emily&#8217;s care at CHOP, it seems to =
be a case of &#8220;the C word&#8221; that physicians can rarely use. </spa=
n><strong>Emily has seemingly been </strong><em><strong>cured</strong></em>=
<strong> of cancer.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Of the first three =
patients dosed with CART-19, two entered remission. Still, despite their ex=
traordinary results, Dr. June and the Penn researchers reached another impa=
sse. They were on the verge of running out of the philanthropic money used =
to treat the first patients, and knew they didn&#8217;t have the resources =
to statistically prove CAR-T&#8217;s efficacy. In 2011, June pushed the tea=
m to publish a pair of reports in </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
m/redirect/855c51bd-5d55-49d2-b9d1-e05c4278c844?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); text-decoration: underline;">The New England Journal of Medicine</a></em=
><span> and </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/4cf5a600-86=
f5-48b1-bf9b-291be1fc6fae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: un=
derline;">Science Translational Medicine</a></em><span> describing their in=
itial findings.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Finally, the world listened. Th=
e papers ripped across the biomedical community and the Penn team was appro=
ached by a wide range of investors and companies. Rather than starting thei=
r own company, June and his team chose the shortest possible path forward f=
or CAR-T to enter the clinic. They decided to license the technology to Nov=
artis, one of the world&#8217;s largest pharmaceutical companies, in exchan=
ge for $20M of upfront funding to manufacture CAR-T at scale for more studi=
es.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In 2017, Novartis made history by gaining ap=
proval to market the CART-19 medicine&#8212;now known as Kymriah (tisagenle=
cleucel)&#8212;for a subset of pediatric and young adult ALL patients. </sp=
an><strong><span>In doing so, Kymriah </span><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
m/redirect/c2d71ae9-ec1d-4ff7-9a51-e448952d9982?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); text-decoration: underline;">became the first FDA-approved gene therapy<=
/a><span>.</span></strong><span> The clinical data leading to its approval =
was nothing short of remarkable. In a multi-center trial with 63 patients, =
83% were in remission within three months.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><spa=
n>Immunotherapy began with an observation about the relationship between fo=
reign bacterial cells and disappearing cancers. Why not try to induce this =
response by systematically adding toxins to tumors? A century of compoundin=
g biomedical progress led to a very different outcome. Rather than introduc=
ing anything foreign into the body, the field achieved a medical first: </s=
pan><strong>a procedure to directly engineer a patient&#8217;s own cells to=
 detect and treat disease.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Kymriah was =
the first major &#8220;killer app&#8221; for the world of cell-based therap=
y. It represented a paradigm shift on the scale of what Genentech accomplis=
hed decades earlier. While Genentech used genetically engineered cells to <=
/span><em>produce</em><span> medicines, CAR-T therapy genetically engineers=
 cells </span><em>for use</em><span> as medicine.</span></p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;"><span>Paradigm shifts have a way of introducing entirely new sets of pro=
blems that require solving, much as scientific answers often lead to dozens=
 of new questions to explore. It&#8217;s the perennial game of whack-a-mole=
 that we call progress. For cell-based therapy, one of the most central new=
 questions is: </span><strong>how</strong><span> </span><strong>can we deli=
ver these new treatments for patients at scale?</strong></p><h2 class=3D"he=
ader-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz=
-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -=
webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: =
rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMac=
SystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color =
Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.625em; font-weigh=
t: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"=
>The looming manufacturing bottleneck</h2><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">When Emily was =
dosed with CAR-T therapy, it was still an academic procedure that required =
highly specific expertise. The entire workflow is far more complex than oth=
er medicines. Isolating T-cells from a patient's blood takes time, and the =
genetic engineering and downstream quality control is non-trivial. Despite =
the extraordinary initial clinical results, there were major open questions=
 around turning CAR-T into a reproducible medicine. In some of the first st=
udies, the cell engineering dragged on for months. In some cases, patients =
died before ever being dosed with the first batch of cells.</p><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;"><span>By the time Kymriah was approved for broader use, Novartis had =
driven the turnaround time down to 22 days. While this represented a hercul=
ean leap forward in process engineering, the price tag for the procedure is=
 still considerable: </span><strong>one dose of Kymriah costs $475,000</str=
ong><span>. Part of this cost can be attributed to the fundamental need for=
 drug developers to recoup their development costs&#8212;Novartis cites the=
 fact that their total R&amp;D spend exceeded $1B. A dose of Kymriah also r=
epresents something very different compared to other medicines: it is a pot=
ential </span><em>cure</em><span> for otherwise untreatable cancers.</span>=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Still, a major question looms over the field. <=
/span><strong>Can the time and cost of a cell-based therapy ever resemble o=
ther medicines?</strong><span> The current manufacturing process for this m=
edicine requires transport of a patient&#8217;s cells&#8212;</span><a href=
=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/c075727f-b665-45c4-a19c-fe00e7ea1362?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">sometimes done via=
 commercial flight</a><span>&#8212;imposing a clear limit on achieving the =
speed and cost of a small molecule pill. First, a patient&#8217;s cells are=
 extracted, frozen, and transferred to a central manufacturing facility, wh=
ere they are engineered to express the CAR-T receptors and screened for qua=
lity. Next, they are frozen again and transferred back to the hospital wher=
e they need to be administered.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, =
64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Thi=
s process barely satisfies the demand for the narrow clinical subset of pat=
ients that meet the criteria for the therapy. The manufacturing bottleneck =
is one of the major reasons why physicians are reluctant to recommend CAR-T=
 therapy, and nearly a third of patients that </span><em>are</em><span> rec=
ommended for the therapy still </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redir=
ect/77c1f83d-3749-4692-8b92-f5c78dc590c7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text=
-decoration: underline;">never receive treatment</a><span>.</span></p><p st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Clearly, this is a huge problem.</strong></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;"><span>Since the first approval for ALL, Kymriah has </span><a hre=
f=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/9e2087a2-fcb2-45b7-b3f5-8b49bb7e6173?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel styl=
e=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">gained approval f=
or two more types of blood cancer</a><span>, and five other CAR-T therapies=
 have entered the market. This is still only scratching the surface. Dozens=
 of labs and biotech companies around the world are vying to create the fir=
st CAR-T therapies for solid tumors, which constitute nearly 90% of overall=
 cancer diagnoses. If the status quo continues, CAR-T therapy could become =
a victim of its own success: </span><strong>it could remain a miracle cure =
that we can&#8217;t scale.</strong></p><div class=3D"captioned-image-contai=
