 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>As the fron=
trunner for successful cellular medicine, immunotherapy also serves as a te=
st bed for how we actually deliver the biological software that we write in=
to a patient's cells. The current paradigm of extracting T-cells from the b=
lood, engineering them, and then reintroducing them is called </span><em>ex=
 vivo</em><span> cell therapy&#8212;which is Latin for </span><em>outside t=
he body</em><span>. As we&#8217;ve seen, this approach introduces a serious=
 scaling limit on clinical adoption of cell-based therapies with our curren=
t manufacturing infrastructure. </span><strong>What if we could engineer im=
mune cells that we could store in biobanks like other biologics, and then u=
se them when we need them?</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); =
font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">This type of &#822=
0;off-the-shelf&#8221; approach is referred to as allogeneic cell therapy, =
because it requires infusing a patient with cells that aren&#8217;t their o=
wn. Much like organ transplants, the major roadblock for allogeneic cells i=
s the threat of graft-vs-host disease, where the body&#8217;s immune system=
 recognizes the cells that are introduced to the blood as foreign and respo=
nds with a frontal assault&#8212;which can be life threatening. Several lab=
s and companies are actively exploring ways to engineer donor cells to evad=
e the immune system.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Achieving this is a hard ge=
netic engineering problem. It would require knocking out two sets of immune=
 receptors, while simultaneously inserting the CAR sequence. </span><strong=
>A key breakthrough that makes this type of multi-edit design potentially f=
easible is CRISPR&#8212;a gene-editing technology that received the 2020 No=
bel Prize for making it possible to programmably edit the genome</strong><s=
pan>. One thing that makes all of this especially mindblowing is that </spa=
n><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/9995057b-5c9b-46ac-a39f-3888f245=
f1dd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" re=
l style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">the seminal=
 CRISPR paper</a><span> was published in 2012, right on the heels of the fi=
rst CAR-T papers.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In one calendar year, w=
e saw field-changing advances for cell-based therapy (the CAR-T papers in 2=
011), gene-editing (the publication of CRISPR gene-editing in 2012), and AI=
 (the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/bdfd0059-78db-449c-9e=
bb-f643a34d8aa7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">=
AlexNet moment</a><span> for deep learning in 2012). 8VC partner Francisco =
Gimenez refers to it as the &#8220;</span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.c=
om/redirect/34d10465-5d3e-4a59-bb89-696a082670ac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 6=
4); text-decoration: underline;">Annus mirabilis</a></em><a href=3D"https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/34d10465-5d3e-4a59-bb89-696a082670ac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rg=
b(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;"> for medicine</a><span>&#8221; =
much like how much Einstein transformed physics with his four publications =
on the photoelectric effect, Brownian motion, relativity, and mass-energy e=
quivalence all in 1905.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>It&#8217;s =
a beautiful example of </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/f5f3=
5bef-a82f-4bb4-9f9a-5676386c4937?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decorat=
ion: underline;">Intertwining Threads</a><span>, as Packy would put it: </s=
pan><strong>&#8220;One of the things that makes the future so hard to predi=
ct is that new technologies don&#8217;t operate in silos; they&#8217;re int=
