n> are pursuing this application&#8212;it also opens the door to differenti=
ating the embryos into other tissues (and potentially organs) with identica=
l genetics to a patient in need of a transplant.</span></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
">Alright&#8230; engineered immune cells to kill cancer, and iPSC/reprogram=
ming therapies to cure, well&#8230; disease.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, =
64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>W=
hat about engineering the microbial cells and communities that inhabit the =
human body?</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>When you first learn that y=
our own cells are outnumbered by your microbial inhabitants, it can be a bi=
t disconcerting. In </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/d518556=
e-fd6e-4c2c-8576-0fc11f335ca1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration=
: underline;">the most recent estimates</a><span>, the human body consists =
of roughly 30 trillion cells&#8212;which is a lot, for sure&#8212;but not a=
s many as the 38 trillion bacteria that live inside us. This vast ecosystem=
 of cells is collectively referred to as </span><strong>the human microbiom=
e.</strong><span> Much like the stages of grief, it&#8217;s possible to mov=
e from a place of fear&#8212;or even disgust&#8212;about this reality towar=
ds a place of awe, and even a reconceptualization of what it means to be a =
human. We all </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/cb3e9258-06ec=
-4c57-8f86-e1a043510f5b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: unde=
rline;">contain multitudes</a><span>. More pragmatically, it opens up an en=
tirely new strategy for interfacing with diseased human cells.</span></p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>So far, the field of microbiome therapeutics has had =
a </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/f98b796d-dcdc-4197-93b9-0=
13627f85284?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">mixe=
d track record</a><span>. First met with extreme hype and a lot of funding,=
 many of the first companies have experienced clinical setbacks. Trials hav=
e been placed on hold for safety concerns. Companies have died. Some of the=
 early science has been </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/4c1=
dd437-bc33-40e5-8122-924fa96bad12?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decora=
tion: underline;">called into question</a><span>. Questions have been raise=
d about the ability to produce consistent and reliable medicines, given tha=
t the first microbiome therapies have been sourced from human poop&#8212;a =
procedure called a fecal microbiota transplant. Seriously.</span></p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;"><span>Despite the shitty start, there are signs that microbiome=
 therapies are starting to reach a higher </span><a href=3D"https://substac=
k.com/redirect/d8be314d-3b1e-40f2-ab68-41e7dd41d96e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64=
, 64); text-decoration: underline;">technology readiness level</a><span>. T=
o start, the </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/d211e506-3f8d-=
47fd-9898-101387c0c488?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: under=
line;">FDA approved the first oral microbiome therapy</a><span> in April ea=
rlier this year. Produced by the Cambridge-based </span><a href=3D"https://=
substack.com/redirect/dce17430-5174-49f7-a728-1e1badade419?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb=
(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">Seres Therapeutics</a><span>, th=
e therapy (called Vowst) contains purified spores from a strain of bacteria=
 capable of outcompeting another strain called </span><em>C. difficile</em>=
<span> that can cause a serious gut infection. The fact that Vowst is going=
 to be co-commercialized by Nestl&#233; indicates that it is ready to be sc=
aled. Name another company that ships top-notch espresso capsules, chocolat=
es, and oral microbiome therapies. I&#8217;ll wait.</span></p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;"><span>Closer to the frontier, things are getting even more sophisticat=
ed. It&#8217;s long been a goal to move beyond working with individual stra=
ins of bacteria. In the &#8220;third pillar&#8221; paper, the authors wrote=
: </span><strong>&#8220;In the future, the microbial community to be transp=
lanted is likely to be an artificial, well-characterized mixture of strains=
=2E&#8221;</strong><span> Why? You don&=
#8217;t want uncharacterized poop, but=
 using only a single bacteria is rate-limiting for complexity. A decade lat=
er, this is becoming a reality. In a massive effort from several top microb=
iome labs at Stanford, researchers created </span><a href=3D"https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/73c41dcc-df72-491a-ba1b-1c71907239c2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 6=
4, 64); text-decoration: underline;">a stable synthetic community of transp=
lantable microbes containing over 100 different organisms</a><span>. Michae=
l Fischbach, one of the &#8220;third pillar&#8221; authors, was a senior au=
thor on this new study. Talk about calling your shots. This type of synthet=
ic microbiome will enable much deeper mechanistic science and more rational=
ly engineered microbiome therapies.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64=
, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>A sta=
ble synthetic microbiome opens the door to some of the more futuristic idea=
s like engineered bugs that sense and respond to their environment, and eve=
n produce small molecules or biologics directly in the body. Given the mega=
-blockbuster sales of the first GLP-1 drugs (like semaglutide) for diabetes=
 and obesity, this gets even more interesting. While semaglutide has been f=
orecasted to potentially </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/42=
255372-99f9-4750-b9bf-458e1718d1ae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decor=
ation: underline;">produce $300B in annual sales</a><span>, the first gener=
ation of medicines has been shown to </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com=
/redirect/3a83f494-3ccb-409e-bfcd-8be1e78d775b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64)=
; text-decoration: underline;">introduce the risk of severe stomach complic=
ations</a><span>. For some of these medicines, </span><a href=3D"https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/5a4b891c-4d8b-40b6-b84c-7ccc7ef020cb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
